%h1.ribbon Get Started with OpenShift

%section
  %h2 From the browser
  %p
    OpenShift offers a brand new (and rapidly improving) web console for creating and managing 
    your apps without ever going to the command line. The console will help you create your first
    application and then show you what you need to do to add additional capabilities like MongoDB, 
    MySQL, or Jenkins continuous integration builds.

  - if previously_logged_in?
    %p= link_to "Open the console now", console_path, :class => 'action-more'
  - else
    %p= link_to "Sign up and use the console now", new_account_path, :class => 'action-more'

%section
  %h2 From the command line
  %p
    If you'd like to use our powerful command line client, the steps below will get you installed 
    and running in just minutes.

%section#install_client_tools
  %h3 1. Install the client tools
  .row
    .span6
      %section#rhel.install
        %h4 Red Hat Enterprise Linux or Fedora
        .hero-unit.prereqs
          %h5 Prerequisites
          %ul
            %li RHEL 6 and up or Fedora 14 and up.
            %li Root or sudoer access
        %ol
          %li
            Download the express repo file
            = link_to 'openshift.repo', "https://openshift.redhat.com/app/repo/openshift.repo"
          %li
            Move the openshift.repo file to your /etc/yum.repos.d/ directory.
            %pre
              $ sudo mv ~/Downloads/openshift.repo /etc/yum.repos.d/
            Replace '~/Downloads/openshift.repo' with the location to which you saved the repo file.
          %li
            Install the client tools:
            %pre $ sudo yum install rhc

          %aside
            %p
              The <code>sudo</code> command will only work if your user is listed in the sudoers file. For more information on setting up sudo, see <a href="http://www.gratisoft.us/sudo/sudo.html">http://www.gratisoft.us/sudo/sudo.html</a>.
            %p
              As an alternative to <code>sudo</code>, you can activate a root terminal with the <code>su</code> command and the root password. In that case, omit <code>sudo</code> from the given commands. Don't forget to close your root terminal when you're done!

      %section#other_nix.install
        %h4 Other Linuxes
        .hero-unit.prereqs
          %h5 Prerequisites
          %ul
            %li Root access
            %li Ruby 1.8 or higher installed or available to be installed
        %ol
          %li
            Install the required packages: git, ruby, rubygems, and the Ruby 1.8 development package.
          %li
            Install the gem:
            %pre $ su -c 'gem install rhc' 
    .span6
      %section#mac.install
        %h4 Mac
        .hero-unit.prereqs
          %h5 Prerequisites
          %ul
            %li
              = link_to 'Full Xcode Suite', 'http://developer.apple.com/xcode'
              &ndash; or &ndash;
            %li
              = link_to 'git for OS X', 'http://code.google.com/p/git-osx-installer/'

        %ol
          %li
            Install the gem:
            %pre
              :preserve
                $ sudo gem install json_pure
                $ sudo gem install rhc

      %section#win.install
        %h4 Windows
        .hero-unit.prereqs
          %h5 Prerequisites
          %ul
            %li
              %a(href="http://www.cygwin.com") Cygwin
            %li
              The following optional cygwin components
              %ul
                %li openssh
                %li ruby
                %li make
                %li gcc
                %li git
        %ol
          %li
            Download and extract rubygems from <a href="http://rubyforge.org/projects/rubygems">http://rubyforge.org/projects/rubygems</a>
          %li
            From within cygwin run:
            %pre $ ruby &lt;path_to_extracted_rubygems&gt;/setup.rb install
          %li
            Install the gem:
            %pre $ gem install rhc

    .span12
      = link_to 'Installing OpenShift client tools video walkthrough', local_video_url('express_client_tools'), :class => 'action-more'

%section#create_domain_name
  %h3 2. Create a domain name
  %p
    Using your OpenShift login and password, call rhc domain create to create a unique domain name for your applications.

    %pre
      :preserve
        $ rhc domain create -n mydomain -l rhlogin
        Password: (type... type... type...)

  %aside
    %p
      OpenShift domain names make up part of your app's url. They are also unique across all OpenShift users, so choose wisely, and be creative!
  %aside
    %p
      The <code>rhc domain create</code> command will create a configuration file - &lt;your home directory&gt;/.openshift/express.conf - which sets up a default login.

%section#create_application.topic
  %h3 3. Create your first application
  %p
    Now you can create an application.
    %pre
      :preserve
        $ rhc app create -a myapp -t php-5.3
        Password: (type... type... type...)
  %p
    This will create a remote git repository for your application, and clone it locally in your current directory.
  %aside
    %p
      OpenShift offers many application stacks. Run <code>rhc app create -h</code> to see all of your options.
  %aside
    %p
      Your application's domain name will be &lt;your app name&gt;-&lt;your domain name&gt;.rhcloud.com. So, the application created by the example commands would be located at myapp-mydomain.rhcloud.com
  %aside
    = link_to 'Creating an application video walkthrough', local_video_url('express_create_app'), :class => 'action-more', :target => '_blank'

%section#publish.topic
  %h3 4. Make a change, publish

  %p
    As we all know, getting an application running is only the first step. Now you are on the road to making it your own.  Here's an example for
    the php framework.

  %pre
    :preserve
      $ cd myapp
      $ vim php/index.php
      (Make a change...  :wq)
      $ git commit -a -m "My first change"
      $ git push

  %p
    Use whichever IDE or editor works best for you. Chances are, it'll have git support. Even if it doesn't, you're just two simple commands away from glory!

  %p
    Now, check your URL - your change will be live.

  %p= link_to 'Deploying an application video walkthrough', local_video_url('express_deploy'), :class => 'action-more', :target => '_blank'

  %aside
    %p
      Checkout these great guides for deploying popular frameworks on OpenShift:
      %ul
        %li= link_to 'TurboGears2 Python framework', 'https://www.redhat.com/openshift/blogs/deploying-turbogears2-python-web-framework-using-express'
        %li= link_to 'Pyramid Python framework', 'https://www.redhat.com/openshift/blogs/deploying-a-pyramid-application-in-a-virtual-python-wsgi-environment-on-red-hat-openshift-expr'
        %li= link_to 'Drupal', 'https://www.redhat.com/openshift/sites/default/files/documents/RHOS_Express_Getting_Started_w_Drupal.pdf'
        %li= link_to 'MediaWiki', 'https://www.redhat.com/openshift/sites/default/files/documents/RHOS_Express_Getting_Started_w_MediaWiki.pdf'

